h the lenses of war, gender, and race, demonstrating that horror comics at this time were centered on white male victimhood and the monstrosity of the gendered and/or racialised other. It is of interest to scholars of horror, comics studies, and American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCold War in comics. 0aHorror comic books, strips, etczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in comics. 0aMen in comics. 0aRace relations in comics. 0aVictims in comics. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aAdventures into the Unknown.  aAmerica.  aCaptain America.  aChamber of Chills.  aCold War.  aComics Code Authority.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aFredric Wertham.  aGreg Sadowski.  aJim Trombetta.  aTales from the Crypt.  aTomb of Terror.  aWarren Publications.  aWitches Tales.  acensorship.  acivil rights.  acomics.  afeminism.  afemninism.  agender.  ahistory.  ahorror comics.  ahorror.  arace.  atrauma.  awar.1 aGoodrum, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613593340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526135933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526135933/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles